0:{"rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","article",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__articlePage","children":[["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"BlogPosting\",\"headline\":\"Deck Landscaping: Integrating Gardens with Your Outdoor Space\",\"image\":[\"https://www.ldndecks.com/images/img03.jpeg\"],\"datePublished\":\"2026-04-17T04:00:00.000Z\",\"dateModified\":\"2026-04-17T04:00:00.000Z\",\"author\":[{\"@type\":\"Organization\",\"name\":\"Loudoun Decks Team\",\"url\":\"https://www.ldndecks.com\"}],\"publisher\":{\"@type\":\"Organization\",\"name\":\"Loudoun Decks\",\"url\":\"https://www.ldndecks.com\",\"logo\":{\"@type\":\"ImageObject\",\"url\":\"https://www.ldndecks.com/ldndecks-logo.webp\"}},\"description\":\"Beautiful decks deserve beautiful surroundings. Learn how to blend your new deck with professional landscaping and vertical gardens.\",\"mainEntityOfPage\":{\"@type\":\"WebPage\",\"@id\":\"https://www.ldndecks.com/blog/deck-landscaping-integrating-gardens\"},\"isAccessibleForFree\":true,\"inLanguage\":\"en-US\",\"speakable\":{\"@type\":\"SpeakableSpecification\",\"cssSelector\":[\".leadParagraph\",\"h1\",\"h2\"]}}"}}],["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__heroSection","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__imgWrapper","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"src":"/images/img03.jpeg","alt":"Deck Landscaping: Integrating Gardens with Your Outdoor Space","fill":true,"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__heroImg","priority":true,"sizes":"100vw"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__imgOverlay","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__containerLarge","children":[["$","$L3",null,{"href":"/blog","className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__backLink","children":"← Back to News"}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__title","children":"Deck Landscaping: Integrating Gardens with Your Outdoor Space"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__meta","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__author","children":["By ","Loudoun Decks Team"]}],["$","span",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__divider","children":"•"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"April 17, 2026"}]]}]]}]}]]}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__contentSection","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__containerNarrow","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__contentBody","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__leadParagraph","children":"Beautiful decks deserve beautiful surroundings. Learn how to blend your new deck with professional landscaping and vertical gardens."}],[["$","p","0",{"children":"A custom deck shouldn’t look like it was just dropped onto your lawn; it should feel like a natural extension of your property’s landscape. By thoughtfully integrating gardens, softscaping, and vertical greenery, you can transform a standalone structure into a seamless outdoor sanctuary."}],["$","h2","1",{"style":{"marginTop":"40px","marginBottom":"20px","color":"#111"},"children":"1. The Power of Skirting with Plants"}],["$","p","2",{"children":"One of the most effective ways to blend a deck with the yard is through transition planting. Instead of leaving the space beneath a low-elevation deck exposed or covered in lattice, consider a dense border of perennial shrubs or ornamental grasses. Plants like Boxwood or hydrangeas provide a lush, living skirt that anchors the deck to the earth and softens the hard architectural lines."}],["$","h2","3",{"style":{"marginTop":"40px","marginBottom":"20px","color":"#111"},"children":"2. Vertical Gardens for Privacy"}],"$L4","$L5","$L6","$L7","$L8","$L9"],"$La"]}]}]}],"$Lb"]}],["$Lc"],"$Ld"]}],"isPartial":false,"staleTime":300,"varyParams":null,"buildId":"Jebrcr4Vyd2YosxlccnHN"}
4:["$","p","4",{"children":"If your deck sits close to a neighbor’s property, you don’t always need a massive privacy wall. Vertical gardens—utilizing trellises and climbing vines—offer a \"living screen\" that provides privacy while keeping the air breezy and fresh. Clematis, Wisteria, or even climbing roses can turn the perimeter of your deck into a vibrant, fragrant wall of color."}]
5:["$","h2","5",{"style":{"marginTop":"40px","marginBottom":"20px","color":"#111"},"children":"3. Integrated Planter Boxes"}]
6:["$","p","6",{"children":"For a truly custom look, we often build oversized planter boxes directly into the deck’s bench seating or railing system. This allows you to bring herb gardens and seasonal annuals right onto the deck surface. It’s perfect for the home chef who wants fresh rosemary or thyme just a few steps from the grill."}]
7:["$","h2","7",{"style":{"marginTop":"40px","marginBottom":"20px","color":"#111"},"children":"4. Lighting the Landscape"}]
8:["$","p","8",{"children":"To make your deck feel larger at night, don’t just light the deck—light the surroundings. Low-voltage uplighting on nearby trees or path lights leading from the deck into the garden creates a sense of depth and prevents the \"black hole\" effect beyond the railing. "}]
9:["$","p","9",{"children":"By treating the deck and the garden as a single design unit, you create a holistic outdoor experience that adds immense value and beauty to your home. Ready to plan your hybrid deck and garden project? Our design team is ready to help you map out the perfect balance of wood and greenery."}]
a:["$","div",null,{"className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__conclusionBox","children":[["$","h3",null,{"children":"Ready to upgrade your outdoor living space?"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"Contact Loudoun Decks today for a free estimate and planning consultation."}],["$","$L3",null,{"href":"/contact","className":"BlogContent-module__WEG1wW__ctaBtn","children":"Get Started"}]]}]
